<font color="#FF0000">STATS UNDER THE GUN </font><br>
<tt>Sat Sep 27 13:10:14 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Joe <br>
I enjoy the information you have provided and perhaps you can help me. I'm looking for information on what the average combat veteran actually experienced as far as actual combat engagement.<br><br>
Over the 13 months I was in country I can say that on at least eight different occassion we engaged hard core NVA for a period of at least four hours or more without breaking contact. <br><br>
At least four of those times the engagement lasted 6-8 hours. <br><br>
Three times we stayed engaged where we knew where they were and they knew where we were and fought off and on til the following morning or afternoon. These types of engagement the brass looked for so that they could deploy more units. Sometimes I think were used as bait. <br><br>
On at least three occassions the firing was fierce. Both in-coming and out going with everything going off all at once for at least 45 minutes to an hour in duration. <br><br>
The other scrimages were minor 30-45 minutes in duration and scattered but in those instances the enemy didn't stay to fight. <br><br>
Snipers and hit and run were numerous but rarely did they cause causalities and because of this were not mentioned in many of our units daily reports.<br><br>
I'm not sure if the fire-fights that lasted longer were because we took causalities or because we had to wait while some of us tried to flank the enemy. <br><br>
I don't know if you have any stats like that. <br>
Until I began posting here and doing the background research for my book, I believed we all (all Vietnam Vets) had experieinced similiar combat situations in Vietnam. It now doesn't appear to be so, and small unit enemy engagement for a time with a regular NVA unit does not seem to have been an experieince many were involved in.<br>
Just wondering, or thinking outloud. If you can help would appreciate the info.<br><br>
In peace and war<br>
Cook
